# Backend: Go

## Project Structure
- Follow standard Go project layout: `cmd/`, `internal/`, `pkg/`
- Keep `main.go` minimal — delegate to internal packages
- Use `internal/` for code that should not be imported externally

## Error Handling
- Return errors as the last return value; never panic for expected failures
- Wrap errors with context: `fmt.Errorf("operation failed: %w", err)`
- Use sentinel errors or typed errors for errors callers need to check
- Check every returned error; do not use `_` to discard errors in production code

## Naming
- Use short, descriptive variable names; single-letter for small scopes
- Exported names are PascalCase; unexported are camelCase
- Interfaces end in `-er` when they describe a single method (e.g. `Reader`, `Writer`)
- Package names are lowercase, single-word, no underscores

## Concurrency
- Prefer channels for communication; use mutexes only for shared state protection
- Always ensure goroutines can be cancelled via `context.Context`
- Use `sync.WaitGroup` or `errgroup.Group` to wait for goroutine completion
- Never start goroutines without a shutdown path

## Conventions
- Use `go vet`, `staticcheck`, and `golangci-lint` in CI
- Format with `gofmt` or `goimports` — non-negotiable
- Write table-driven tests using `testing` package
- Use `context.Context` as the first parameter for functions that do I/O
- Prefer dependency injection; avoid global state
